PetFinder.my Adoption prediction¶

Udacity Data Science nano-degree capstone project¶

Project overview¶

The project was taken from a kaggle competition. To summarize the idea: We want to improve abandoned animals welfare (especially dogs/cats) by quicker adoption. PetFinder.my has been Malaysia’s leading animal welfare platform since 2008, with a database of more than 150,000 animals. Animal adoption rates are strongly correlated to the metadata associated with their online profiles, such as descriptive text and photo characteristics. The beauty in the project is that it's well formulated, contains lots of various data types (thus allows to practice many aspects of the course) and is a real life problem.

Problem Statement¶

Develop an alogrithm that ranks the adoptability of pets - specifically, how quickly is a pet adopted? This is a multiclass classification problem with 5 classes: (Although it can also be considered a regression problem)

  • 0 - Pet was adopted on the same day as it was listed.
  • 1 - Pet was adopted between 1 and 7 days (1st week) after being listed.
  • 2 - Pet was adopted between 8 and 30 days (1st month) after being listed.
  • 3 - Pet was adopted between 31 and 90 days (2nd & 3rd month) after being listed.
  • 4 - No adoption after 100 days of being listed. (There are no pets in this dataset that waited between 90 and 100 days).

Strategy for solving the problem¶

In my mind and with the knowledge from this course and Coursera deep learning specialization.

  1. Build upon previous works --> Scanning through kaggle kernels of the competition in order to understand the data and get an initial working direction.
  2. Exploratory data analysis.
  3. Quick and dirty classification:
    • ETL pipeline for data.
    • Use some generic classifier with small params grid search.
    • Analysis (metrics).
  4. Write down list of ideas for improvement.
  5. Start work iterations in the following manner:
    • Update ETL pipeline if required.
    • Update classification.
    • Analysis -> Test for improvement.
  6. Repeat until close to weighted kappa score of 0.3. (Around position 1500 in leader board, though I aspire for a score of 0.4, which should )

Metrics¶

The competition metric is the quadratic weighted kappa (qwk), which measures the agreement between two ratings. I wasn't familiar with it prior to this exercise. A nice explanation can be found here or here. Why is it justified? Accuracy could have been a good metric because by definition we're interested in accurate predictions and we're not very afraid of FN or FP (Perhaps then we'd like to use precision/recall as metrics). The qwk is similar to accuracy but also attempts to consider the number of accurate predictions that were derived by chance.

Data Exploration (cnt.)¶

From the exploration above, we see that for the training data we have:

  • Slight imbalance between dogs cats (approx. 45/55 split)
  • Imbalanced labels, specifically, low number of pets adopted on the 1st day. ("Ideal scenario")
  • Approximately 93% of pets in data are from 4 (out of 14) states in Malesia.
  • Neglecting the name (which I don't think is relevant), there are only 12 missing descriptions. (negligble).
  • For about 12% of animals we're unsure about their vaccination/dewormed/sterlized status.
  • Some listings (small fraction) don't have a Google sentiment analysis.
  • Most listings have photos but only a fraction have videos.
  • There are no duplicated values.
  • A LOT of listings contain more than one pet!
  • From the age distribution we see that it's similar between dogs/cats. Also, most dogs are young (< 2years)

So, to summarize, in terms of the ETL pipeline, the "abnormalities" we'll have to deal with are:

  • Some columns which I don't see any use of (Name, RescuerID, ...) which I'll drop.
  • few missing descriptions. (Don't care about names).
  • Some missing sentiments.
  • If photo raw data is required, some missing photos.
  • Imbalances in labels. (Will impact training).
  • I DO NOT ENCODE CATEGORICAL VARIABLES because they're already in numerical format, and I plan to use a tree based classifier so one-hot encoding isn't recommended. (see here)
  • Imbalances between number of dogs/cats in database (More on that later).
  • Imbalances between number of pets per state.
  • Listings with multiple pets. (Not sure yet how to approach this...)

Analysis¶

We see 2 trends:

  • 1st, dogs and cats behave DIFFERENTLY, regarding what "features" impact the adoption speed. This agrees with the kaggle kernel discussed previously.

  • The most influencing ORIGINAL features (later, we'll generate more features) are:

    For dogs:

    • Age (Positive correlation. Older (higher value of age) dogs are waiting more for adoption)
    • Quantity (Positive correlation. The more dogs the longer it takes to adopt)
    • Fur length (Negative correlation. The more fur (higher value) the quicker (lower value) dogs get adopted).
    • Sterilization (Negative correlation. The "higer" the value (not sterlized or unsure) the quicker dogs are adopted)

    For cats:

    • Same relations with age and quantity as dogs.
    • Similar relations to dogs with sterilization and fur length, but for cats, sterilization (specifically, no sterlization) correlates more to faster adoption.

In general:

  • It seems that the dominant features correlating to adoption speed are very similar between cats and dogs, even though the correlation values are different.
  • It seems that the amount of photos/videos isn't strongly related to adoption speeds which is good. I think that later on, adding a NN that extracts feature images might help, that is to say, I believe the content of the images may help.
  • As an example, I'll also plot the "distribution" of adoption speed vs. fur length. We expect to see lower adoption values for higher fur values.

Background¶

  1. Reminder (Ensemble methods): These methods can be divided to either bagging or boosting. Obviously, (by the name), we're talking about boosting. Short reminder: Boosting is a method that has multiple weak learners that are improved sequentially. Each learner cost function gets "punished" (increased weights) on the misclassified points of the previous learner and thus is "boosted".

  2. Gradient Boosting: GBM wasn't learned in the current course. It's an ensemble method of boosting. In simple terms:

    • Define $x$ the parameter we want to etimate.
    • at stage 'n', our estimator is a function of 'x', e.g. $F_n(x)=y_{estimated}$.
    • Ideally, we would like to have an $h(x)$ function such that $F_{n+1}(x)=y_{true}=F_n(x)+h(x)$
    • In other words: $h(x)=y_{true}-F_n(x)$
    • Notice that if we have a squared error loss $0.5(y-F_n(x))^2$, $h(x)$ is the gradient!

Therefore, gradient boosting will fit $h$ to the residual $y-F_n(x)$, and by "fitting" I mean it will try to find an approximation that will minimize the average value of the loss function on the training set. (An approximation can be some curve for a polynomial regression problem, for example).

  1. XGBoost is an "extreme" version of Gradient Boosting. It can run over parallel processors and even on parallel machines (such as clusters in the cloud...). LightGBM (My preferred method) is similar in performance but runs faster.
  1. NLP: Some more elaboration here... I implemented 2 NLP methods as part of the ETL pipeline. They are used for conversion of the "description" field. One method uses word embeddings, and converts the words of the description to 300 elements vectors from a pruned corpus originally generated by Google. The representation is the averaged vector of all words. The 2nd option (which I chose to use) is generating a TF-IDF bag of words from all descriptions and vectorizing the descriptions. For both methods I reduced the dimensionality (after testing it) via SVD because the LightGBM/XGBoost tend to overfit (We get a very high training score but still not good CV result)

Analysis¶

  • I created 3 initial LightGBM models. One for cats, one for dogs and one for both. Their performance differs. It seems that the dog classifer is much better than the cat classifier, and that the combined classifier is an average between the two.

  • It was very important for me to plot the learning curves. From them, We notice 2 trends:

    • Training QWK increases (Error is reduced) the more samples we have.
    • CV QWK increasing (Error is reduced) the more samples we have.

Using this I conclude that my training is still overfitting the data because there's a large gap between training and CV performance.

The summary of the results is:

Score Dogs only Cats only Combined
Train 0.72 0.68 0.72
CV 0.39 0.3 0.358

  • I want to check feature importances, and attempt to remove "non important" features.

Feature importances¶

  1. From the initial correlation we examined in the data, we expected the following features to impact:

    • Age --> Almost highest LGB gain.
    • "sterilization" --> Medium gain.
    • State --> Medium gain.
    • Fur length --> Low gain.

  2. Actually, the highest factors are the NLP analysis and the sentiment of the description.

  3. BTW - What is "gain" in LGBM? The definition: Total decrease in node impurity (same role as information gain) weighted by the probability of reaching that node averaged over all trees of the ensemble.(The probability approximated by the proportion of samples reaching that node)

Bottom line: There is some matching between correlations and feature importances, but not too much.... Some features we didn't check because there's no meaning to correlation for numerical encoding of them (dog breeds, for example) however, they might be important. Example: 'Breed1'.

Every end is the beginning of something new...¶

In this (long) markdown cell i'll follow the rubric and recap/explain the chain of events. Let's begin with the bottom line: At the beginning of the road, WITHOUT NLP (not seen in the notebook) the basic model scored 0.345. After all the goodies I managed to climb to 0.37.

Having said that, let's go over the rubric:

Metodology¶

I'll elaborate about the feature engineering I did between steps and the initial and final results. Most of it was just adding/removing new columns of data that required different processing.

  1. First iteration was quick and dirty. Just using tabular data with dropout of columns and removing small value of NaN items. Inital QWK was: training: 0.507, CV: 0.336, Test set: 0.39
  2. I attempted to separate processing to the dataset to dogs/cats based on different correlations in the data.
  3. Later I added the sentiment analysis (to the separated datasets, +1 feature vector)
  4. Recombined dogs/cats because I arrived to the conclusion that there's no point in processing them independently.
  5. Added the Google sentiment analysis. (+1 feature vector)
  6. Attempted to drop less important features (simplify the model to reduce overfit) according to feature importances. (-3 feature vectors)
  7. Decided to extract the description field via NLP. Implemented 2 different methods (Embedding and TF-IDF transformations) --> +10 feature vectors.
  8. Passed the first photo of each PetID through a ResNet-18 --> +10 feature vectors.
  9. Extraced 3 features (sum,mean,var) for the size,width,height of all photos per PetID --> +9 feature vectors.
  10. At that stage, Final QWK was: training: 0.71, CV: 0.37, Test set: 0.41

In between the steps, I changed between XGBoost to LightGBM (for faster training speeds) and attempted a lot of hyperparameters optimization, though I reached the conclusion it's hardly worth the time. Better invest in data manipulation.

Results - Model Evaluation and Validation¶

Model Evaluation and Validation: I chose to work with the LightGBM over the XGBoost model due to it's speed. (Much faster). As I explained in the background, this is an Ensemeble method which works via Gradient boosting.

I'll start with a RECAP:

  1. In the course we learned about decision trees and creating boundaries for data classification via splitting the data in such a way that each step attempts to reduce the Entropy of the data (Gain information) via splitting the data in some manner.

  2. We then advanced to Ensemble models. Decision trees tend to overfit, so we want to use many of them in some way for reduction in variance. We learned about Adaptive Boosting. It begins by fitting a weak classifier (say, decision tree), classifier on the original dataset and then fits additional copies of the classifier on the same dataset but where the weights of incorrectly classified instances (and thus, changes the sample distribution) are adjusted such that subsequent classifiers focus more on difficult cases.

  3. Now, Gradient Boosting achieves the same goal (focusing on "harder/misclassified points") in a different manner. We fit a weak learner and observe the errors. We then continue to fit another weak learner, but this time on the errors (residuals) themselves and then add the result to our previous weak learner with some learning factor. This continues iteratevely and actually implements gradient descent because, for a squared error loss function, the residuals are the negative derivate, so adding a negative derivatie is a gradient descent step.

  4. LightGBM/XGBoost are advanced implementations for the gradient boosting.

Let's discuss our final model qualities: It's a LightGBM model with the following parameters:

  • Has max depth of 12 (No more splits beyond that).
  • Learning rate (like in gradient descent) of 0.1.
  • Feature fraction: The fraction of features selected for building a tree at each iteration (80%)
  • Bagging fraction: The fraction of data used for each iteration. (85%)
  • min_split_gain: Minimum loss reduction required to make a further partition on a leaf node of the tree. I chose 0.03.
  • min_child_samples: The minimum number of points in a leaf or else won't split. I use a rather large value (200) in order to reduce overfitting.
  • min_child_weight: From documentation: "Minimum sum of instance weight (hessian) needed in a child (leaf)". I'm not sure about this one.. :\

The important qualities of this model is:

  1. It is an ensemble method that uses many "weak" classifiers to improve.
  2. It can learn non-linear functions (based on decision trees).
  3. It is also a super fast implementation.

The method I used to validate my results is both calculating the QWK score over the test set AND K-Fold cross validation. I also plotted the learning curve from which I could get a sense if the model is biased or overfitted. Unfortunately, it currently overfits. Simplifying it just degrades the training performance but doesn't improve the CV results.

Justification¶

A summary of my final results:

  • Training QWK: 0.71
  • CV QWK: 0.37
  • Test set QWK: 0.41

The Kappa score is an interesting metric. It measures accuracy of predicted labels, but then it also attempts to adjust for the probability of the algorithm and trusted labels assigning items to the same category "by chance". However, Kappa does not take into account the degree of disagreement between observers and all disagreement is treated equally as total disagreement. Therefore, when the categories are ordered, we use Weighted Kappa and assigns different weights $w_i$ to incorrect labels. How do we assing this weights? We use linear weights when the difference between the 1st and 2nd category has the same importance as a difference between the 2nd and 3rd category, etc. However, if the difference between the 1st and 2nd is less important than a difference between the 2nd and 3rd category, etc., we use quadratic weights.

So it makes sense in our case. The more we "miss" the adoption waiting period, our prediction is worse.

What do my results reflect?

  1. Overfitting: A large gap between CV and training results means the model doesn't generalize well. Even though I attempted to select parameters to reduce the overfit, it's still something I suffered from.

  2. Overall low QWK:

    • From my test set results, about 57% Are INCORRECTLY classified.
    • From the incorrectly classified points about 58% Miss by '1' unit of adoption speed, the rest miss by more.

  3. Current model might benefit more training samples (according to the CV slope in the learning curve. It might improve a bit).

  4. Importance analysis for features was presented and will be discussed shortly.

why some approaches worked better than others?¶

What approaches worked well for me? And in contrast to what?

  1. More data features (but also which ones) led to the greatest improvements, contrary to only the original data. It's obvious why. The extra data is correlated to the adoption speeds, and thus, adding and handling it Correctly should have an extra benefit. For example, it's obvious that photos and images will impact (for most people) the decision about adoption, thus, not using it limits our potential performance.
  1. Regarding the images, the extracted ResNet-18 features had much less impact than the metadata of sizes/width/height. It's difficult to analyze why. I ASSUME that either the features extracted at the layer I extracted aren't similar to what we expect (That deeper layers represent more complex features such as dog faces --> relate more to adoption)

OR Perhaps the SVD dimensionality reduction had some impact. (Can't see why, since I tested many options and most of the data variability is explained in my selection)

OR It's just that the metadata, which is correlated to photo quality, is much more correlated to the adoption speed than just the content of the image.

OR Wrong network architecture, wrong features. I didn't actually test how these features looked.

  1. Why did TF-IDF transformation worked better than embedding? I suspect this is because the distribution of words in the corpus of the embedded description matches the text descriptions less well than deriving a corpus from the descriptions themselves.

  2. Why LightGBM worked better than XGBoost? It didn't! What it did was to train faster, and that's invaluable. The difference arises due to different implementations, but this is out of scope for this report.

Conclusion¶

Reflection¶

Let's recap the problem and end to end solution. We have dogs/cats data we want to predict the adoption speed. Our scoring method is based on QWK which is similar to accuracy. Our data is diverse (tabular, textual, metadata, images). The end to end solution contains:

  1. Data exploration, correlations analysis, checking for problems in the data (Missing values, duplicates, etc.).
  2. Building an ETL pipeline to convert and aggregate the data from numerous sources into pandas dataframe.
  3. Training a GBM classifier over the data with iterations.
  4. Between iterations, more data was added/removed, hyperparameters were updated in an attempt to improve the score. examples of improvements were written in the "results" section above.

There are 2 aspects of the projects which I found difficult and interesting:

  1. The 1st is the entire Kaggle world. This is the 2nd time (1st one was for writing a data science blog using the Deep Solar Dataset i'm working on a dataset from there. Contrary to the 1st time where nobody handled that data yet, here I joined an active competition, a week before the deadline, with thousands of participants, experts, kernels, etc.. I was a bit overwhelmed by all the info, discussions and approaches for solving the problem and also the competitive edge. I ranked pretty lousy (though it wasn't my final model, didn't have time to support both this exercise and my kernel on Kaggle), but it opened my eyes to vast amount of data science and knowledge that can be gained through competitions. Moreover, I discovered that there are actually courses aimed at teaching people how to win competitions.

  2. Improving the classifier in iterations: It seemed that it's very hard to improve the models I built. Moreover, even when my model CV score improved, my public Kaggle score in the LB didn't improve and it was difficult to debug.

    • Which features do I use? Which ones I drop?
    • How much metadata to use?
    • What other external features (example: population size in states of Malesia?) should I bring.
    • When handling text, which embedding?
    • When handling images, which network?
    • ...

    It seems that these decisions are critical for utilizing my time effectively, and I need to develop a formal "strategy" for making these choices.

    • ...

  1. So, how would I change my implementation with the objective of scoring a higher QWK score?

    • I would concentrate all the extra data generation at the beginning of the code, after the ETL pipeline. (Current code adds more data along the way and it's annoying).

    • I would modify functions to support 2 types of input. Training/Testing. This would make it more easier for me to run an actual test set (not cross validations). (Because I added data along the way, inserting a test set data into the ETL pipeline isn't enough, I have to run more functions again.. This isn't the best implementation. I need a more ordered pipeline).

    • I would work directly in the Kaggle Kernel, or at least do regular copies from my local environment to the Kaggle kernel, test and commit there as well. (I currently developed only on my notebook and when attempting to develop on Kaggle, had to modify some parts of the code)

    • I would study the supplied test set and perform comparisons of distribution differences between it and the training data. (I didn't even check this currently, because my goal was to finish the capstone project, not winning the Kaggle competition).
